			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_64466559">		 &lt;<a href="mailto:drink%40hyperlogos.org">drink@hyperlogos.org</a>&gt;
		on Sunday May 12, 2024 @07:58AM (<span class="ind"></span><a href="//hardware.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23319911&amp;cid=64466559">#64466559</a>)
		<small><a href="http://hyperlogos.org/" title="http://hyperlogos.org/" class="user_homepage_display">Homepage</a>
<a href="//slashdot.org/~drinkypoo/journal/" title="Sunday September 17, 2023 @09:53AM" class="user_journal_display">Journal</a> </small>
</span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64466559"><p>What I have been saying since we started seeing the "SMRs will solve everything wrong with nuclear" argument is that per-unit costs will make them more expensive, not cheaper. More reactors for the same output means for example more welds to make, which means more X-ray inspections of welds which can wind up costing more than the welds themselves (which is why the automated welding they're doing on prototypes isn't going to solve the problem.) The small reactors still need all the same stuff as the big ones. If you're trying to get the same output on a site then not only are you magnifying your costs by building many reactors instead of one, but you're also multiplying the costs of making connections to those reactors from the water source and so on.</p><p>Everything tends to get cheaper per unit of output as it gets larger until it reaches the point where it's so large that its very size causes new engineering problems. Why would SMRs ever have been different? It just never made any sense that doing more work to arrive at the same level of output would be cheaper.</p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64466559">
<span class="ind"></span><a id="reply_link_64466559" class="btn link" href="//hardware.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23319911&amp;op=Reply&amp;threshold=1&amp;commentsort=0&amp;mode=thread&amp;pid=64466559" onclick="D2.replyTo(64466559); return false;">Reply to This</a> 	<a href="#" class="comment_share_toggle btn link">Share</a>
	<div class="comment_share sharethis-0 hide"><span class="au"></span>
		<a class="t slashpop" href="https://twitter.com/intent/tweet?text=Yes obviously%20by%20drinkypoo%20%40slashdot%20https://hardware.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23319911&cid=64466559" target="_blank">twitter</a>
		<a class="f slashpop" href="https://www.facebook.com/sharer/sharer.php?u=https://hardware.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23319911&cid=64466559" target="_blank">facebook</a>
