	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64466701"><p><div class="quote"><p>&gt;"The money invested in nuclear energy would save far more carbon dioxide if it were instead invested in renewables,"</p><p>But they are not doing the same job unless they also include storage.  Plus the output could still be inconsistent if generation was too low for too long (due to not enough storage or freaky weather).  And if that storage is lithium batteries, you have to add in all that life cycle carbon, as well.</p></div><p>To quote from the article: "In comparison, the cost of each megawatt-hour of electricity from wind and solar photovoltaic plants is around AUD$100 [as opposed to AUD$400-600 for SMRs], <em>even after accounting for the cost involved in balancing the variability of output from solar and wind plants.</em>" (emphasis added by me).</p></div>
	</div>

