</li><li id="tree_64466927" class="comment full contain"><span class="ind"></span>
<div id="comment_status_64466927" class="commentstatus"></div>
<div id="comment_64466927" class="cw">
	<div id="comment_top_64466927" class="commentTop newcomment">
		<div class="title">
			<h4><a id="comment_link_64466927" name="comment_link_64466927" href="//hardware.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23319911&amp;cid=64466927" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(64466927)" >Re:Perhaps the only problem they could solve...</a>


		 	<span id="comment_score_64466927" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 64466927); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>5</a>, Interesting)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a href="//slashdot.org/~Sique">Sique</a>  <span class="uid"><a href="//slashdot.org/~Sique">( 173459 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_64466927">		
		on Sunday May 12, 2024 @11:55AM (<span class="ind"></span><a href="//hardware.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23319911&amp;cid=64466927">#64466927</a>)
		<small><a href="http://127.0.0.1/" title="http://127.0.0.1/" class="user_homepage_display">Homepage</a> </small>
</span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64466927">They should. But they don't.
<p>
Molten Salt reactors are known since 70 years now, as the first experimental one was running in 1954, the ASR. A second one was built 60 years ago, in 1964, and ran until 1969, clocking up two years of actual operation, an availability of about 50%, the MSRE
</p><p>
Those are the only two Molten Salt reactors ever being operational. Everything else was just theory. Most close to completion was the Molten Salt Breeder, but this one was never completed, as to work as a breeder, it would have had a positive temperature coefficient, making it close to become supercritical.

Why, after 70 years of experience with an actual molten salt reactor, are there no viable plants actually producing electricity? To me, Molten Salt reactors look like the reactor equivalent of Anna Kournikova: They look nice, but they never win a single's tournament.</p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64466927">
<span class="ind"></span><a id="reply_link_64466927" class="btn link" href="//hardware.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23319911&amp;op=Reply&amp;threshold=1&amp;commentsort=0&amp;mode=thread&amp;pid=64466927" onclick="D2.replyTo(64466927); return false;">Reply to This</a> <span class="ind"></span><a class="btn link" href="//hardware.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23319911&amp;threshold=1&amp;commentsort=0&amp;mode=thread&amp;cid=64466841" onclick="return D2.selectParent(64466841)">Parent</a> 	<a href="#" class="comment_share_toggle btn link">Share</a>
